name: Fred Ehrsam
tweet: Net: Strong pushback against giving brainteasers (when properly administered and weighted) seems like BS, and potentially a sign of broader cultural weakness.

name: Fred Ehrsam
tweet: Brainteasers can be “needle in a haystack” problems and thus solve rate is random even by capable candidates: Possible, but largely mitigated by choosing better problems, and still better off with the signal.

name: Fred Ehrsam
tweet: Interviewers can overweight brainteasers: Possible, but correctable. In my view, they are helpful as one of many inputs.

name: Fred Ehrsam
tweet: Sometimes people have seen the problem before: This is often detectable, and even if they have and successfully fool the interviewer that they haven’t, still better to have the signal across many candidates.

name: Fred Ehrsam
tweet: Steelmans against brainteasers:

name: Fred Ehrsam
tweet: It’s probably not a coincidence that high frequency trading firms, which are brutally competitive, seem to all use them extensively.

name: Fred Ehrsam
tweet: There actually may be signal in the refusal to do a brainteaser. I’m having trouble imagining someone who is actually high horsepower adamantly refusing to do one.

name: Fred Ehrsam
tweet: As one of many factors in an interview, I find brainteasers give a lot of signal. Imagine giving a group of kids a few brainteasers. You’re telling me there’s no signal in the ones who are able to solve more of them?

name: Fred Ehrsam
tweet: The even funnier thing is that the naysayers were external recruiters, either paid or at one of our venture firms. In retrospect I think they cared more about their reputation and not offending candidates than making the best possible candidate assessment.

name: Fred Ehrsam
tweet: The vibe I got, which is even more clear in retrospect, is that candidates were scared.

name: Fred Ehrsam
tweet: I think this is total BS. Someone’s ability to apply logic is a critical input to how well they might perform in any role, and a challenging logic problem is one helpful way to assess that.

name: Fred Ehrsam
tweet: It was made to seem impolite, even offensive. It was made to seem as if they provided no signal on a candidate. It was made to seem as if, if a brainteaser was administered, that would somehow determine the entire outcome of the interview.

name: Fred Ehrsam
tweet: One thing that really bothered me as a young founder: at some point I was told it was impolite to give “seasoned executives” brainteasers in interviews.

name: Fred Ehrsam
tweet: Since anyone can own a piece of crypto infrastructure, people are paying attention much earlier in its development than prior infrastructure-level technologies. This is a double-edged sword, and we're seeing the pros and cons of this dynamic play out in real time.

name: Fred Ehrsam
tweet:
Abridged internet breakthroughs timeline, for perspective:
1969: ARPANET
1982: TCP/IP
1993: HTML
1990-1994: Web browsers
1994-1998: Search engines
1999: SaaS
2003-2004: Social media
1999-2007: Mobile
2009-present: Crypto

We're 28-53 years in, depending on your start date.

name: Fred Ehrsam
tweet: This is because most people have little reason to pay attention to new technologies before the mainstream application breakthroughs. Almost no one paid attention to the early infrastructure period of the internet 1969-1994.

name: Fred Ehrsam
tweet: One thing most people don't fully grasp: it takes years, often decades, to go from a new infrastructure-level technology breakthrough (like crypto) to a vibrant ecosystem of mainstream applications.

name: Fred Ehrsam
tweet: It's the people who are using the tech, and thus understand its novel properties, who discover the breakthrough applications. They discover the "uniquely enabled" applications that use the new tech to do what was impossible before, and end up being the most valuable.

name: Fred Ehrsam
tweet: There is a strong tendency towards skeuomorphic ideas at the beginning of any new technology. Humans reason by analogy and we only know what we have seen in the past. This leads to horse drawn cars, film for recording plays, telephones for relaying morse code, etc.

name: Fred Ehrsam
tweet: Entrepreneur quantity and quality flowing into the ecosystem astonishes daily, tackling everything from centralized infrastructure (brokerages, exchanges, custodians), to crypto-native financial tools (DeFi), to new ways of owning and using digital media (NFTs).

name: Fred Ehrsam
tweet: Today, almost 10 years later, crypto is a sprawling ecosystem quickly redefining money, the financial system, and, ambitiously, the internet itself.

name: Fred Ehrsam
tweet: Yet crypto kept building. @ethereum came on the scene and showed that crypto native applications were possible, opening up a whole new world of possibilities.

name: Fred Ehrsam
tweet: There was serious hardship. In the 3 years between 2014 and 2017, the outside world thought crypto was dead. Over a third of employees left.

name: Fred Ehrsam
tweet: Over time, crypto grew, and so did the company. A simple #Bitcoin wallet evolved into individual and institutional products to support a blossoming cryptoeconomy. 2 nerds who met on the internet (yes, @brian_armstrong and I met on @reddit) turned into a company of 1000+.

name: Fred Ehrsam
tweet: We were far from conventional. For our first hire, we selected a whip smart fanatical lumberjack over a Google manager.

name: Fred Ehrsam
tweet: Beginnings were not glamorous. @coinbase launched out of a two bedroom apartment we shared with another company.

tweet:

@coinbase had one mission: to make crypto easy to use.

name: Fred Ehrsam
tweet:
Lots making the point that prediction markets fluctuated due to "new information".

A great model predicts the future, changing the idea of "new information". For example, a great model could predict the outcome of individual states (the "new info" moving markets) pre-election.

name: Fred Ehrsam
tweet:
@Disruptepreneur True but tautological: "market prices reflect market sentiment".

If I predicted 11% Trump (current market) and didn't change my prediction over the last 24 hrs, that certainly didn't reflect sentiment, but my predictive power was high, and the point is predictive power.

name: Fred Ehrsam
tweet:
@elliot_olds This is true in a general sense.

I also suspect more accurate models could have been formed without any information from the last 24 hours.

name: Fred Ehrsam
tweet:
Prediction markets and the election:
The lesson is *not* that prediction markets are more accurate than other sources today. They fluctuated wildly. 

However, they *are* the key to better predictive power tomorrow. Better models will be created if they can be directly monetized.

tweet: @jacksondahl Easy to miss because we normally conceptualize frontiers as "outward". The frontier of ourselves as humans, however, is "inward".

name: Fred Ehrsam
tweet:
@jacksondahl Thiel cited 3 key frontiers in 2009:
1) Cyberspace
2) Outer space
3) Seasteading

He got a lot right but missed the one right under our nose: ourselves. Brain/computer interfaces, genetic engineering, bio-augmentation, and new methods of introspection.

https://t.co/T9cSkxrdQ4

name: Fred Ehrsam
tweet:
@jacksondahl Internet is massive frontier, although restricted over last 5-10yrs as small number of platforms dominate. Virtual worlds are an extension.

Crypto is a key new frontier. Permissionless, uncensorable. Rare place where 2 ppl in garage can still change the world.

name: Fred Ehrsam
tweet: A truly aligned coach seeks to make themself obsolete.

name: Fred Ehrsam
tweet:
Excellent leaders create the conditions to help others reach higher levels. Specifically, they create holding environments that allow others to build a consciousness bridge from one order to the next. These environments are extremely rare.

Here is an example in student coaching: https://t.co/mjtIdPdx3D

name: Fred Ehrsam
tweet: Order 5 ("Self-Transforming Mind"): Ability to generalize across abstractions (advanced systems level thinking). Able to step outside own frame when looking at systems. Kegan estimates less than 1% of all adults become self-transforming.

name: Fred Ehrsam
tweet: Order 3 ("Socialized Mind"): Ability to construct durable categories and think across them (beginnings of systems level thinking). Experience others as sources of internal validation, orientation, or authority. Most adults.

name: Fred Ehrsam
tweet:
There are 5 stages of adult development in Kegan's model. A few of the stages (what he calls "Orders"):

Order 0: Total inability to grasp concepts or separate any experiences from the self. Are subject to everything occurring around then. Newborn babies are Order 0.

name: Fred Ehrsam
tweet:
Very useful as a framework for improving as a manager, in relationships, and in thinking broadly.

Good Stanford Psychology summary here: https://t.co/PsLvVSYQRY

name: Fred Ehrsam
tweet:
Psychologist Robert Kegan's work on stages of adult development has been one of the most influential on me in the last year (thanks @GrahamDuncanNYC)

In short, Kegan believes development is the ability to make object what was once subject, unlocking higher level systems thinking

name: Fred Ehrsam
tweet:
The hardest part of starting a network is overcoming the initial "chicken and egg" problem.

Like equity in a startup, early users can be rewarded with disproportionate ownership, incenting them to help overcome this bootstrapping problem.

name: Fred Ehrsam
tweet:
Crypto is a breakthrough in distribution model: it turns users into economically aligned distributors.

Users as distributors powers the network effects of many Web 2.0 companies (eg join Insta because friends on it). Economic alignment supercharges it.
